# CSRD Physics & Annotation Rules

## 1. Units MUST be explicit and documented

All distances are **meters**. All frequencies are **Hz**. All powers are **dBm** unless suffixed `_dB`.
Never quietly multiply by 1000 to convert km<->m. If a toolbox helper expects a different unit
(e.g. some `gaspl` variants use km), wrap it in a thin `metersToHelperUnit` helper and document it.

```matlab
% BAD - silently treated meters as kilometers, 60 dB error
freeSpacePL = fspl(obj.Distance * 1000, obj.WaveLength);

% GOOD - meters in, meters used
freeSpacePL = fspl(max(obj.Distance, 1), obj.WaveLength);
```

## 2. Planned values are NEVER fabricated from realized values

`Planned` reflects what the planner asked for. `Realized` reflects what the executed signal
actually produced. If the producer did not populate `Planned`, leave it as an empty struct -
do not copy `Realized` into `Planned` to make annotations look complete.

```matlab
% BAD
sourceInfo.Planned.Bandwidth = comp.Bandwidth;  % this is realized, not planned!

% GOOD
if isfield(comp, 'Planned') && isstruct(comp.Planned)
    sourceInfo.Planned = comp.Planned;
else
    sourceInfo.Planned = struct();
end
```

## 3. Link budget noise bandwidth must be clamped

When computing analytical SNR, the noise bandwidth must be the smallest positive among
{configured, receiver Fs, transmitter occupied BW}. Otherwise narrow-band signals carry
a systematically pessimistic SNR label.

Use `csrd.utils.linkbudget.resolveNoiseBandwidth` - do NOT reinvent the picker locally.

## 4. Distinguish AnalyticalPathLoss from AppliedPathLoss

When a channel block (e.g. ray tracing) returns its own path loss, store that in
`AppliedPathLoss`. The FSPL the planner reasoned about goes in `AnalyticalPathLoss`.
Keep both so AI/ML consumers can audit drift.

## 5. Sample rate must come from the producer

Modulators MUST set `SampleRate`. Channel blocks MUST set `SampleRate` (or pass it
through). When `SampleRate` is missing or `<= 0`, raise `CSRD:Core:MissingSampleRate`
with frame / Tx / segment context. Never back-derive from `length(Signal)/Duration`
or hardcode `200e3`.
